For Spring, the simplest way is to use [Databricks JDBC driver][1] that provides very good performance, especially when you need to fetch big chunks of the data.  Driver is available on the [Maven Central][2] under following coordinates:

```
&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;com.databricks&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;databricks-jdbc&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;version&gt;2.6.34&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;scope&gt;runtime&lt;/scope&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;
```

After that you can just use it as another JDBC data source via JDBC url like `jdbc:databricks://...` (exact string depends on the configuration).  I have a [small example][3] of using it from Spring (not very idiomatic although).

Another way is to use [Databricks SQL Statement Execution REST API][4], but it&#39;s typically requires a bit more work to authenticate, wait for results, decode data, etc.  Although the [Databricks Java SDK][5] simplifies its usage, so you can use it if you don&#39;t want to use JDBC.


  [1]: https://docs.databricks.com/en/integrations/jdbc-odbc-bi.html
  [2]: https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/com.databricks/databricks-jdbc
  [3]: https://github.com/alexott/databricks-playground/tree/main/spring-jdbc-dbsql
  [4]: https://docs.databricks.com/api/workspace/statementexecution/executestatement
  [5]: https://github.com/databricks/databricks-sdk-java

