If you want to replace only a specific substring in Java, you can use the `replaceFirst` method or manipulate the string using the `substring` method. Here&#39;s an example using `replaceFirst`:

```java
String str = &quot;gallbladder&quot;;
str = str.replaceFirst(&quot;allb&quot;, &quot;o&quot;);
System.out.println(str);  // This will print &quot;goladder&quot;
```

Alternatively, you can achieve this using `substring` if you know the index or use `indexOf` to get the index first:

```java
String str = &quot;gallbladder&quot;;
int index = 1; // Index of the &#39;a&#39; you want to replace
str = str.substring(0, index) + &quot;o&quot; + str.substring(index + 1);
System.out.println(str);  // This will also print &quot;gollbladder&quot;
```

These methods will replace only the first occurrence of &#39;a&#39; in the string.

Yes, you can achieve your desired behaviour by using the `substring` method to build a new string with the replacement. Here&#39;s how you can replace only the first occurrence of &#39;a&#39; with &#39;o&#39; in the string &quot;gallbladder&quot;:

    String str = &quot;gallbladder&quot;;
    int index = str.indexOf(&quot;a&quot;);
    
    if (index != -1) {
        String newStr = str.substring(0, index) + &quot;o&quot; + str.substring(index + 1);
        System.out.println(newStr);
    } else {
        // Handle the case when &#39;a&#39; is not found in the string.
        System.out.println(&quot;Substring not found&quot;);
    }

*In this code, we first find the index of the first occurrence of &#39;a&#39; using the indexOf method. If &#39;a&#39; is found, we create a new string by concatenating the substring before the &#39;a&#39;, the replacement &#39;o&#39;, and the substring after &#39;a&#39;. This way, only the first &#39;a&#39; is replaced with &#39;o&#39;, and the rest of the string remains unchanged.*

If you always want to replace **1st** matching substring, you can use &quot;replaceFirst&quot; method.

        String str = &quot;gallbladder&quot;;
        str = str.replaceFirst(&quot;a&quot;, &quot;o&quot;);
        System.out.println(str);

Otherwise if you want to replace different index, you can write a code like below. Lets say you want to replace 3rd(2nd index) &quot;al&quot; from &quot;gallblaldd aleral&quot;

        String str = &quot;gallblaldd aleral&quot;;
        String stringToReplace = &quot;al&quot;;
        String replaceWith = &quot;o&quot;;
        String[]  splitStrings= str.split(stringToReplace);
        int matchingIndexToReplace = 2;
        int index = 0;
        str = &quot;&quot;;
        for (String s : splitStrings) {
            if (index == matchingIndexToReplace) {
                str = str + s + replaceWith;
            } else if (index != matchingIndexToReplace &amp;&amp; (index != (splitStrings.length - 1) || matchingIndexToReplace != (splitStrings.length - 1))) {
                str = str + s + stringToReplace;
            } else {
                str = str + s;
            }
            index++;
        }

        System.out.println(str);

In your particular case, I prefer the use of `replaceFirst`, which has already been demonstrated.

If, however, you need something a little more complicated, you should consider making use of a `StringBuilder`, as a, very basic, example...

    String str = &quot;gallbladder&quot;;
    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(str);
    int index = str.indexOf(&#39;a&#39;);
    sb.replace(index, index, &quot;*&quot;);
    str = sb.toString();

This essentially acts like a mutable `String`

Here&#39;s a regex approach to replace the nth occurrence of a string:

    String replace(String str, String find, String replace, int occurrence) {
		return str.replaceFirst(&quot;((?:&quot; + find + &quot;.*?){&quot; + (occurrence - 1) + &quot;})&quot; + find, &quot;$1&quot; + replace);
	}

Basically, the replacement `$1` refers to the outer capturing group which matches any text containing the search string `n - 1` times, followed by the replacement for the final occurrence.

For brevity&#39;s sake I left out escaping, but if you don&#39;t know the contents of `find` and `replace`, you may need to wrap them in `Pattern.quote()` and `Matcher.quoteReplacement()` respectively.

